    "summary": "The Awan dynasty of Elam, approximately 2700–2100 BC, represents one of the earliest known political entities in the region of modern southwestern Iran. Elam — centred on the Khuzestan plain and the highland regions of the Zagros Mountains — was a distinct civilisation with its own language, script (Proto-Elamite), and cultural traditions that developed in close but contentious relationship with Mesopotamia. The Awan dynasty, the earliest named Elamite dynasty recorded in the Sumerian King List, maintained both conflict and commerce with the Sumerian city-states to the west.\n\nThe Awan kings appear in Mesopotamian sources as both enemies and treaty partners of Sumerian rulers. The [[event:1722|Akkadian Empire under Sargon]] brought Elam under its political domination for a period, and Elamite nobles of the Awan period used Akkadian as an administrative language. However, Elamite cultural identity remained distinct, and Elam subsequently threw off Akkadian overlordship as part of the broader collapse of Akkadian power. An Awan king was one of the signatories to the oldest known treaty in world history — a written agreement with the Akkadian king Naram-Sin preserved on a clay tablet.\n\nElam played a crucial role in Bronze Age commercial networks as a source of metals, stones, and other goods from the Iranian plateau and as a conduit for commodities flowing between Central Asia and the Persian Gulf. The later Elamite civilisation that would destroy the [[event:1724|Third Dynasty of Ur]] and remain a significant power in the Near East for over a millennium had its roots in the political and cultural institutions developed during the Awan period.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Awan_dynasty",
